(5,'index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=78','index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=78:how-do-solar-panels-work&catid=21','How do solar panels work?',' We don\'t want to bore you with the nitty-gritty physics details, but at a high level, solar panels work by using sunlight to generate electricity through the photovoltaic effect. The process starts with solar cells, which absorb light, knocking electrons (aka carriers of electricity) loose. These electrons then flow, creating direct current (DC) electricity. Metal plates on the sides of each solar cell transfer the DC electricity to wires. At this point, inverters (more on these below) convert the DC electricity into alternating current (AC) electricity, which most common household appliances use. And voila  your solar panels have produced solar energy for your home! ','2023-11-24 07:18:40','baf640959e7a3b9d9878024e28cbfb72',1,1,1,'*','2023-11-23 22:38:49',NULL,'2023-11-23 22:38:49',NULL,0,0,4,'O:52:\"Joomla\\Component\\Finder\\Administrator\\Indexer\\Result\":19:{i:0;i:1;i:1;s:5:\"en-GB\";i:2;s:680:\" We don\'t want to bore you with the nitty-gritty physics details, but at a high level, solar panels work by using sunlight to generate electricity through the photovoltaic effect. The process starts with solar cells, which absorb light, knocking electrons (aka carriers of electricity) loose. These electrons then flow, creating direct current (DC) electricity. Metal plates on the sides of each solar cell transfer the DC electricity to wires. At this point, inverters (more on these below) convert the DC electricity into alternating current (AC) electricity, which most common household appliances use. And voila  your solar panels have produced solar energy for your home! \";i:3;a:25:{s:2:\"id\";i:78;s:5:\"alias\";s:24:\"how do solar panels work\";s:7:\"summary\";s:962:\"<p>We don\'t want to bore you with the nitty-gritty physics details, but at a high level,<a href=\"https://www.energysage.com/solar/solar-panels-work/\">solar panels work</a>by using sunlight to generate electricity through the photovoltaic effect. The process starts with<a href=\"https://www.energysage.com/solar/solar-photovoltaic-cells/\">solar cells</a>, which absorb light, knocking electrons (aka carriers of electricity) loose. These electrons then flow, creating direct current (DC) electricity. Metal plates on the sides of each solar cell transfer the DC electricity to wires. At this point, inverters (<a href=\"https://www.energysage.com/solar/#solar-inverters\">more on these below</a>) convert the DC electricity into alternating current (AC) electricity, which most common household appliances use. And voila your solar panels have produced<a href=\"https://www.energysage.com/about-clean-energy/solar/\">solar energy</a> for your home!</p>\";s:4:\"body\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"images\";s:173:\"{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}\";s:5:\"catid\";i:21;s:10:\"created_by\";i:42;s:16:\"created_by_alias\";s:0:\"\";s:8:\"modified\";s:19:\"2023-11-24 07:18:40\";s:11:\"modified_by\";i:42;s:6:\"params\";O:24:\"Joomla\\Registry\\Registry\":3:{s:7:\"\0*\0data\";O:8:\"stdClass\":68:{s:14:\"article_layout\";s:9:\"_:default\";s:10:\"show_title\";s:1:\"1\";s:11:\"link_titles\";s:1:\"1\";s:10:\"show_intro\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"show_category\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"link_category\";s:1:\"1\";s:20:\"show_parent_category\";s:1:\"0\";s:20:\"link_parent_category\";s:1:\"0\";s:11:\"show_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:11:\"link_author\";s:1:\"0\";s:16:\"show_create_date\";s:1:\"0\";s:16:\"show_modify_date\";s:1:\"0\";s:17:\"show_publish_date\";s:1:\"1\";s:20:\"show_item_navigation\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"show_vote\";s:1:\"0\";s:13:\"show_readmore\";s:1:\"1\";s:19:\"show_readmore_title\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"readmore_limit\";s:3:\"100\";s:10:\"show_icons\";s:1:\"1\";s:15:\"show_print_icon\";s